@NODE MENU_Index "Index menu"

 @{b}The Index Menu@{ub}

  This menu holds the filenames of the files currently stored. By choosing
  one of them the file will be shown. Just as if you selected it from the
  @{"index" LINK MI_Index}

  If no files are stored the index menu will disappear.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_Clear "Project menu"

 @{b}Clear@{ub}

  If a file is being viewed, no matter what type it is (ASCII or an
  AmigaGuide document), it will be flushed from memory.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_ClearAndReturn "Project menu"

 @{b}Clear and return@{ub}

  Clears the file being viewed and returns to the screen Vinci was last
  opened from.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_ClearAll "Project menu"

 @{b}Clear all@{ub}

  Flushes all files from memory. A file does not have to be viewed for
  this function to work.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_LoadNew "Project menu"

 @{b}Load new@{ub}

  Load a file. If a file is being viewed it file will be cleared.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_LoadAndShow "Project menu"

 @{b}Load and show@{ub}

  Load a file. Adds a file to the list of stored files and views it.

  If a file is an @{"archive" LINK Archivers} a list will be made of the contents and you
  will then be able to select a file to extract. If the file you want to
  extract is another archive it simply opens another window with
  the contents of this file! Even if it for example is an LZX within a
  LhA archive.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_LoadFromFileBase "Project menu"

 @{b}Load from file base@{ub}
 
  Load a file from the file base. Doubleclick on an entry in the listview
  and it is loaded and shown.
 
  The window can be resized and the position and size are saved when you
  @{"save" LINK MI_SaveSettings} settings.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_LoadFromPathBase "Project menu"

 @{b}Load from path base@{ub}

  If you have specified any paths in the path base a window with them will
  appear. By selecting one of the paths it will be used as the current
  directory.

  If you cancel the path window (by pressing escape) the file requester
  will still appear.
 
  The path window can be resized and the position and size are saved when
  you @{"save" LINK MI_SaveSettings} settings.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_LoadAsAmigaGuide "Project menu"

 @{b}Load as AmigaGuide@{ub}

  When loading files Vinci acts as are they AmigaGuide documents and
  therefore tries to show in them in an AmigaGuide window.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_LoadAsText "Project menu"

 @{b}Load as text@{ub}

  When loading files Vinci acts as are they normal text files. This way
  you can load an AmigaGuide document as a normal text file.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_Reload "Project menu"

 @{b}Reload@{ub}

  Clears the file currently being viewed and reloads it. Useful after
  having edited in the file.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_Print "Project menu"

 @{b}Print@{ub}

  Print a file to either 'PRT:' or another destination.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_Save "Project menu"

 @{b}Save@{ub}

  Save a file. If you do not select a new file you will have to confirm an
  overwriting of it.
  
  Useful if you have loaded a crunched file and want to save it in an
  uncrunched format.

  NOTE: You cannot save an AmigaGuide document because Vinci does not
        buffer these files. It only stores the filename in memory.
       
        I strongly advise you NOT TO SAVE anything else but text files.
        The saved file will NOT work properly or at all if it is e.g. an
        executable or a picture.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_History "Project menu"

 @{b}History@{ub}

  Select this and you will get a window with the last 1-999 loaded files.

  For more information check out @{"Files" LINK MI_Files} settings.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_Index "Project menu"

 @{b}Index@{ub}

  If there are more than 1 file stored this window will show them in a
  Listview gadget. You can doubleclick or press return on an entry and
  it will be viewed. Use the up and down cursor keys to scroll through
  the list. Pressing shift or alt with a cursor key will move the
  selected entry respectively 2 or to the top/bottom. Pressing escape
  or the close gadget will cancel the selection.
 
  The window can be resized and the position and size is saved when you
  @{"save" LINK MI_SaveSettings} settings.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_Hide "Project menu"

 @{b}Hide@{ub}

  Hides Vinci. Press the popkey to make it appear or use @{b}Exchange@{ub}.

  If the Hide menu item is ghosted (you can not select it) it is because
  you have entered a invalid popkey. It is invalid if it is in use by some
  other program or if it has been written incorrectly. Refer to your
  Workbench for how to enter a popkey.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_About "Project menu"

 @{b}About@{ub}

  Miscellaneous information on Vinci.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_Quit "Project menu"

 @{b}Quit@{ub}

  Quits Vinci. If settings have been changed and you have not saved them a
  requester will inform you about that and give you the possibility to
  either Save them, Quit or (only in some cases) Cancel quit.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_Search "Search menu"

 @{b}Search@{ub}

  Vinci has as some quite advanced features when it comes to text
  searching. Wildcard search and a history for instance. The search window
  should not be too difficult to figure out.
  
  The @{b}Match color@{ub} setting is a actually to numbers. Let's set it
  to 13. This would not be processed as'thirteen' but as '1' and '3' - the
  background color and the foreground color for the match.

  It is not possible to search in an AmigaGuide document unless you load
  it as a text file.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_SearchPrevious "Search menu"

 @{b}Search previous@{ub}

 Searches for the previous occurence of the search string. If the search
 string is empty it will request a string.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_SearchNext "Search menu"

 @{b}Search next@{ub}

 Searches for the next occurence of the search string. If the search string
 is empty it will request a string.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_Set "Marks menu"

 @{b}Set@{ub}

  Choosing one of the sub items and the current line number of the text
  file you are viewing will be stored.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_GoTo "Marks menu"

 @{b}Go to@{ub}

  Choose one of the sub items and Vinci will jump to the marked location
  immediately. If an item is ghosted it is (obviously) because you have
  not stored a mark there.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_Sort "Marks menu"

 @{b}Sort@{ub}

  Will sort the marks so the mark with the lowest line number will be the
  first one and so on. Therefore, if you f.x. have line 103 assigned to F4
  and line 53 to F8 they will after a sort be rearranged so that F1 will
  have line 53 and F2 103.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_PreloadBase "Miscellaneous menu"

 @{b}Preload base@{ub}

  The name says it all, no? Preload base is a list of files which will be
  loaded the first time Vinci is started. This is probably not a feature
  you want all the time so you therefore you may specify IGNOREPRELOAD as
  an CLI argument and the preload base entries will be ignored.

  Anyway if you press @{b}Add@{ub} a requester pops up and you can select
  BOTH directories and files. Selected entries will appear the listview
  gadget. Doubleclicking or pressing return on a highlighted entry will
  activate the string gadget placed below the listview. Now WHY is a
  string gadget so great you ask? Well, because you can add a pattern to
  an entry. For example you want the some 'C' include files from an
  include directory and not the assembler files which end with ".i". For
  those of you who are not familiar with these strange include files I
  will just explain to you that include files holds various important
  information for programmers.

  You could have the following as an entry:

   INCLUDES:dos/#?.h
 
  This entry will load ALL files in that directory which ends with ".h"
  and ALL files in this directory's subdirectories as well!!

  Press @{b}Remove@{ub} to remove an entry. You must of course first select an
  entry :-)
 
  Press @{b}Sort@{ub} to sort the entries alphabetically.
 
  You may load previously saved entries by pressing @{b}Load@{ub} and selecting a
  file. The current list will be flushed the second you confirm the
  selection of a file.

  To save the entries press @{b}Save@{ub} and select a file to save to.

  NOTE: You will not be notified about changes to the list when you quit
        Vinci so remember to save the entries before you quit.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_FileBase "Miscellaneous menu"

 @{b}File base@{ub}

  Have you wanted easy access to a lot of files? Yes! Well, me to. So
  instead of going through endless links of directories I have created
  the @{b}File Base@{ub}.

  Adding, removing and sorting entries works in exactly the same way as in
  @{"Preload base" LINK MI_PreloadBase}.

  If there are no entries @{"Load specified..." LINK MI_LoadFromFileBase} will be ghosted.

  As an example to what you could use @{b}File base@{ub} for I can say that I
  mostly use it for easy & fast access to include files, BBS file lists,
  docs and lyrics. Could not live without it :)

  Just select @{"Load specified..." LINK MI_LoadFromFileBase} from the menu and select
  the file you wish to load and magic will happen.
 
  You may load previously saved entries by pressing @{b}Load@{ub} and selecting a
  file. The current list will be flushed the second you confirm the
  selection of a file.

  To save the entries press @{b}Save@{ub} and select a file to save to.

  NOTE: You will not be notified about changes to the list when you quit
        Vinci so remember to save the entries.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_PathBase "Miscellaneous menu"

 @{b}Path base@{ub}

  Usually when I select a file, it is located in a directory which I often
  access when using Vinci. For example my directory with BBS file lists.
  The problem was that I found it tedious because I always had to work my
  way through those darn sub directories to get to a file. I do not know why
  but some say that I have an organized HD.. Maybe it is all those sub
  directories I have!? :-) (Get to the bloody point, Martin) Okay, okay..
  ehh.. well, instead of working your way through all those sub directories
  you can now via this @{b}Path base@{ub} easily add "the common" directories to a
  list which could e.g. be forced to pop up every time before you load a
  file. See @{"Files..." LINK MI_Files}

  Adding, removing and sorting entries works in exactly the same way as in
   @{"Preload base" LINK MI_PreloadBase}.

  If there are no entries @{"Load from path base..." LINK MI_LoadFromPathBase} will be ghosted.

  Use @{"Load from path base..." LINK MI_LoadFromPathBase} if you want to load a file from a
  directory you have added to the list.
 
  You may load previously saved entries by pressing @{b}Load@{ub} and selecting a
  file. The current list will be flushed the second you confirm the
  selection of a file.

  To save the entries press @{b}Save@{ub} and select a file to save to.

  NOTE: You will not be notified about changes to the list when you quit
        Vinci so remember to save the entries.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_EditASCII "Miscellaneous menu"

 @{b}Edit ASCII@{ub}
 
  Launch the ASCII editor to edit the file you are viewing.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_Edithex "Miscellaneous menu"

 @{b}Edit hex@{ub}

  Launch the hex editor with the file you are viewing.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_Info "Miscellaneous menu"

 @{b}Info@{ub}

  Shows information on the current file, marks in the current file and
  memory consumption. I think most of the information is pretty obvious
  and need no explanation but there are a couple of things I would
  like to explain.

  @{b}File memory use@{ub} is the sizes of the stored files added together along
  with the memory they use for e.g. line indexes.

  @{b}Largest memory block@{ub} gives you an estimate of how large a file you
  will be able to store in Vinci BEYOND the already stored files.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_FlushWorkPath "Miscellaneous menu"

 @{b}Flush work path@{ub}

  When Vinci decrunches or extracts files it uses the @{"work path" LINK MI_Decrunching} for
  the decrunched/extracted file.

  Files extracted from archives are not deleted afterwards and decrunched
  files which are AmigaGuide are also not deleted since they are needed.
  Other decrunched files are treated accordingly to the @{"temp file" LINK MI_Decrunching}
  setting.

  The bottom line is that the more files you decrunch and extract the less  
  memory/disk space (wherever you have your work path) will be free.
  Therefore, you may flush the work path (delete all the files in the work
  path. Depending on the @{"decrunch settings" LINK MI_Decrunching} a console window will be
  opened on the screen and the DOS Delete command will start deleting. You
  can therefore at any time during deletion press Control-C to stop it
  when the console window is active!
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_JumpToLine "Miscellaneous menu"

 @{b}Jump to line@{ub}
 
  Select the line you wish to jump to by typing it in the requester.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_TextFont "Miscellaneous menu"

 @{b}Text font@{ub}

  To switch between the two text fonts simply select the one not in use.
  @{b}First@{ub} is @{"Text font" LINK MI_GUI} and @{b}Second@{ub} is @{"2nd text font" LINK MI_GUI}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_GUI "Settings menu"

 @{b}GUI@{ub}

  Pressing @{b}Okay@{ub} affects Vinci immediately. Pressing @{b}Cancel@{ub} will abort
  the changes you have made.

  @{b}Screen Mode@{ub}

   Select the screen mode you want Vinci to be in.

   The screen is public so you may open other windows on Vinci. The name
   of the screen is 'VINCI'.

  @{b}Public screen name@{ub}

   If you always want Vinci to appear on a specific public screen such as
   f.x. the Workbench you could enter the name of the screen here. The
   alternative is to specify the name each time on the command line.

  @{b}Screen font@{ub}

   This font is used for everything which does not require a fixed font.
   E.g. the menus.

  @{b}Text font@{ub}

   This font is used for the text and the info bar in the bottom.

  @{b}2nd text font@{ub}

   As of version 1.4 of Vinci you can switch between two fonts. This one
   and the above. Great if you stumple upon a PC text which usually
   requires an IBM sort of font. Only non-proportional fonts are supported
   here.

  @{b}Palette@{ub}

   Set the colors to suit your personal taste.

  @{b}Information bar@{ub}

   Represents the appearance of the information bar. May be one of three:

    @{fg highlight}Standard@{fg text}

     Will use color 0 as background for the information.

    @{fg highlight}Checkers@{fg text}

     Will use a checkered background pattern for the information.

    @{fg highlight}None@{fg text}

     If you do not want it at all. If you select this you will get MUCH
     faster scrolling especially in ANSI mode. You will also get an extra
     line :)

  @{b}Scroller@{ub}

   Specifies where should the scroller be placed.

    @{fg highlight}On right side@{fg text}

     On the right side of the screen.

    @{fg highlight}On left side@{fg text}

     On the left side of the screen.

    @{fg highlight}None@{fg text}

     The scroller is not used.

  @{b}Scroller width@{ub}

   The width of scroller on the right side of the main window.

  @{b}Listview scroller width@{ub}

   The width of the scrollers in listviews.

  @{b}Hide AppIcon@{ub}

   If you do not want the AppIcon present on the Workbench tick this.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_Decrunching "Settings menu"

 @{b}Decrunching@{ub}

  Pressing @{b}Okay@{ub} affects Vinci immediately. Pressing @{b}Cancel@{ub} will abort
  the changes you have made.

  @{b}Work path@{ub}

   This is used for the decrunching/extracting of files so select a
   path which is of NO importance e.g. 'T:' which is the default. A
   decrunched (not extracted) file will always have the name:
  
   '<temp path>Vinci.temp'

  @{b}Auto create@{ub}

   If ticked the above path will be created when selecting @{b}Okay@{ub} and
   whenever you start Vinci. I suggest you have a work path called
   'RAM:Vinci' and then tick @{b}Auto create@{ub}.

  @{b}Flush on exit@{ub}

   If ticked Vinci will delete all in the work path when you exit Vinci.
   This requires that you have the standard 'Delete' CLI commando
   available.

  @{b}Confirm@{ub}

   Confirm flushing of work path.

  @{b}Quiet@{ub}

   All output of the flushin process will be sent to NIL:. In plain
   English: It will not open a window.

  @{b}Temporary file@{ub}

   Signifies what Vinci should do to the temp file after it has decrunched
   it. May be one of these three:

    @{fg highlight}Delete@{fg text}

     Delete the temp file without asking you.

    @{fg highlight}Request@{fg text}

     Asks you if it should delete the temp file.

    @{fg highlight}Ignore@{fg text}

     Ignores the temp file.

  @{b}Auto decrunch@{ub}

   Tick this if Vinci should automatically decrunch and extract files.

  @{b}Auto close extract window@{ub}

   If ticked the window used to list the contents of LhA/LZX archives will
   be closed after the first file has been extracted.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_Files "Settings menu"

 @{b}Files@{ub}

  Pressing @{b}Okay@{ub} affects Vinci immediately. Pressing @{b}Cancel@{ub} will abort
  the changes you have made.

  @{b}Tabulator size@{ub}

   Tabulator size can be set from 1 to 16.

  @{b}Index menu@{ub}

   Tick if you want the index menu to be active.
 
  @{b}View mode@{ub}

   The view mode of AmigaGuide documents may be one of these three:

    @{fg highlight}Synchronous@{fg text}

     When the AmigaGuide document is shown it blocks for all other input
     to Vinci.

    @{fg highlight}Asynchronous@{fg text}

     The AmigaGuide document uses a separate process which controls it.   
     This allows you to view several AmigaGuide documents at the same
     time.

    @{fg highlight}As text@{fg text}

     When loading a NEW file it will not be checked if it is an AmigaGuide
     document. This way you can load AmigaGuide documents and search in
     them. (I said it would be possible to search in AmigaGuide documents :)

   NOTE: You can not convert an AmigaGuide document loaded when view mode
         was set to @{b}Synchronous@{ub} or @{b}Asynchronous@{ub} by changing view mode to
         @{b}As text@{ub}. This must happen at load time.

  @{b}Auto quit@{ub}

   If you want to automatically quit Vinci after you have viewed an
   AmigaGuide document tick this. BUT! To be able to quit after having
   viewed an AmigaGuide document the following things must be obeyed:
  
    - There must only be 1 file in the index (the AmigaGuide document).
    - The AmigaGuide document must have been opened by one of the
      following:
   
      - As an argument from the CLI.
      - As a preloaded file.
      - Icon selected with Vinci. NOT dropped onto the AppIcon.
      - Chosen from the @{"Index" LINK MI_Index}.
      - Loaded by @{b}Load new@{ub} or @{b}Load and show@{ub}.

  @{b}Startup@{ub}

   This specifies how Vinci should request a file when it is first
   started. Four ways:

    @{fg highlight}Load and show@{fg text}

     The original way. Pops up a file requester.

    @{fg highlight}Load from file base@{fg text}

     Just the same as if you selected this from the menu.

    @{fg highlight}Load from path base@{fg text}

     Just the same as if you selected this from the menu. .. Is there an
     echo in here?

    @{fg highlight}None@{fg text}

     Vinci will not request a file.

  @{b}Load all as AmigaGuide@{ub}

   If ticked all files will be loaded as are they AmigaGuide documents.

  @{b}Pop up paths@{ub}

   If ticked a window with all the paths you have entered in the path base
   will appear when you want to load a file. If you select a path it will
   be the default path for the file requester.

  @{b}History file@{ub}

   This is the file which holds the unique names of the last 1-999 loaded
   files.

  @{b}Remember@{ub}

   How many different filenames should be remembered.

  @{b}Sort@{ub}

   Tick this to sort the history list alphabetically.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_ARexx "Settings menu"

 @{b}ARexx settings@{ub}

  Pressing @{b}Okay@{ub} affects Vinci immediately. Pressing @{b}Cancel@{ub} will abort
  the changes you have made.

  @{b}Items@{ub}

   The names of the items.

  @{b}Name@{ub}

   The name of the selected item.

  @{b}Add@{ub}

   Add a script or a separator bar.

  @{b}Remove@{ub}

   Remove a script or a separator bar.

  @{b}Up@{ub}

   Move an entry upwards.

  @{b}Down@{ub}

   Move an entry downwards.

  @{b}Sort alphabetically@{ub}

   Sort the entries alphabetically.

  @{b}Script@{ub}

   The script to execute.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_Miscellaneous "Settings menu"

 @{b}Miscellaneous@{ub}

  Pressing @{b}Okay@{ub} affects Vinci immediately. Pressing @{b}Cancel@{ub} will abort
  the changes you have made.

  @{b}Popkey@{ub}

   Any commodity needs a popkey and this is it. When pressing the popkey
   combination Vinci will unhide itself or move its screen and window to
   the front. Every second time you press the popkey sequence Vinci will
   show the screen from which it was opened on. Example: You open Vinci
   with a custom screen while Workbench is the frontmost screen. Then if
   you press the popkey Vinci will move the Workbench screen to the front.

  @{b}Popup at start@{ub}

   Tick this if you want Vinci to show its GUI when it is first loaded.

  @{b}ASCII editor@{ub}

   The editor you want to use for editing text files. You must append a
   '%s' (without the apostrophes) to the editor. This tells Vinci where to
   put the filename. If there are spaces in the filename you need to put
   a pair of quotation marks around '%s'.

   Example: @{b}MyEditor "%s"@{ub}

  @{b}Hex editor@{ub}

   The editor you want to use for editing binary files. Look above for
   more information.

  @{b}Edit file@{ub}

   If you do not want to use the original file for editing you can make
   Vinci copy it to the name of this string gadget and use this instead.
   If you do not want this then clear it and the original filename will
   be used.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_SavePalette "Settings menu"

 @{b}Save palette@{ub}

  If ticked Vinci will save the palette for the screen it is on. Otherwise
  it will save the palette it got from the last loaded settings file.

  This is a useful feature if you want to resize the main window of Vinci
  on a public screen but do not want to alter your palette which might differ
  from the palette of the public screen your on.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_LoadSettings "Settings menu"

 @{b}Load@{ub}

  Load settings. Requests the filename of the settings file you want to
  load.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_SaveSettings "Settings menu"

 @{b}Save@{ub}

  Save settings.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_SaveAsSettings "Settings menu"

 @{b}Save as@{ub}

  Save settings. Requests the filename of the settings file you want to
  save.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MI_ExecuteScript "ARexx menu"

 @{b}Execute script@{ub}

  Choosing this will pop up a file requester where you can select an ARexx
  script which will then be executed.
@ENDNODE

@NODE CLI "The CLI"

 @{b}The CLI@{ub}

  You can type 'Vinci ?' to see the command line interface of Vinci.

  It looks like this:

  F=FILE/M,A=ALL/S,I=IGNOREPRELOAD/S,C=CLEARALL/S,C=CLEARCURRENT/S,
  P=PUBSCREEN/K,X=WINX/N,Y=WINY/N,W=WINWIDTH/N,H=WINHEIGHT/N

   @{b}FILE@{ub} abbreviated F
   
    The file(s) you want loaded. Supports pattern matching.
   
   @{b}ALL@{ub} abbreviated A

    If specified, subdirectories will be entered too.

   @{b}IGNOREPRELOAD@{ub} abbreviated I

    Specify this if you do not want the preloaded entries to be loaded.

   @{b}CLEARALL@{ub} abbreviated C

    Flushes all buffers in Vinci.

   @{b}CLEARCURRENT@{ub} abbreviated C

    Flushes the current buffer in Vinci.

   @{b}PUBSCREEN@{ub}

    If you want Vinci to open on a public screen you can specify a name
    for it here. This argument overrides any settings in @{"GUI settings" LINK MI_GUI}.

    E.g. '1:> Vinci P=Workbench' would make Vinci appear on the Workbench
    screen if it is open that is.

   @{b}WINX@{ub}

    The left edge of the text window on a public screen. This and the
    following 3 arguments overrides stored positions and dimensions if
    they are specified.

   @{b}WINY@{ub}

    The top edge of the text window on a public screen.

   @{b}WINWIDTH@{ub}

    The width of the text window on a public screen.

   @{b}WINHEIGHT@{ub}

    The height of the text window on a public screen.
@ENDNODE  

@NODE Keyboard "Keyboard usage"

 @{b}Keyboard usage@{ub}

  Numeric keypad is abbreviated NKP.


  Key combination            Effect
  ---------------            ------
  
  Cursor UP                  Scroll 1 line up
  NKP 8

  Cursor DOWN                Scroll 1 line down
  NKP 2

  Cursor UP + ALT            Scroll 2 lines up
  NKP 8 + ALT

  Cursor DOWN + ALT          Scroll 2 lines down
  NKP 2 + ALT

  Cursor UP + SHIFT + ALT    Scroll 4 lines up
  NKP 8 + SHIFT + ALT

  Cursor DOWN + SHIFT + ALT  Scroll 4 lines down
  NKP 2 + SHIFT + ALT

  Cursor UP + SHIFT          Scroll a page up
  NKP 8 + SHIFT
  NKP 9

  Cursor DOWN + SHIFT        Scroll a page down
  NKP 2 + SHIFT
  NKP 3

  Cursor UP + CONTROL        Move to start of buffer
  NKP 7

  Cursor DOWN + CONTROL      Move to end of buffer
  NKP 1

  Cursor LEFT                Move to previous buffer
  NKP 4

  Cursor RIGHT               Move to next buffer
  NKP 6

  Cursor LEFT + SHIFT        Move to first buffer
  NKP 4 + SHIFT

  Cursor RIGHT + SHIFT       Move to last buffer
  NKP 6 + SHIFT


  F1 - F10 work as markers and pressing one of those with a shift key
  will store the current line. Pressing it without a shift key will
  make it jump to the stored line.
  
  Pressing backspace causes the text to refresh. The reason for this
  feature is that the scroll speed will become and stay slow if Vinci had
  to display colors in other than the first bitplane. A search match or an
  ANSI code sequence that changes the color to e.g. blue will make the
  scroll speed slow. You should only press backspace when all the text
  shown on the screen is written in pen 1 (usually black). Otherwise it
  will not have any effect.

  To make it more comfortable moving around in Vinci while doing ya
  thang I have added some convenient keyboard shortcuts:

   Key   Function
   ---   --------
    C    Clear
    L    Load new
    W    Load and show
    F    Load from file base
    P    Load from path base
    A    Load as AmigaGuide
    T    Load as text

    I    Index

    H    Hide
    Q    Quit

    S    Search
    B    Search previous
    N    Search forward

  These shortcuts are localized and therefore vary from language to
  language.

  Pressing 'Help' will load the Vinci documentation provided it has been
  installed properly!
@ENDNODE

@NODE Archivers "Archivers"

 @{b}Supported archivers@{ub}

  Currently only two archivers are supported but those are also the most
  used. They are:

   - LhA
   - LZX

  I may implement other archivers such as Zip and Arj.. I do not know if
  anyone wants it? It is no trouble to implement, just my lazyness that
  keeps me from doing it :-)
@ENDNODE

@NODE Paths "Paths"

 @{b}Special paths@{ub}

  As of version 1.6 you can use a file to specify an alternative path for
  settings (Vinci.prefs).

  For the settings file the name is PREFSPATH.

  The file must be placed in either the directory where Vinci is run from
  or in 'ENV:Vinci'.
@ENDNODE

@NODE ARexxInterface "ARexx interface"

 @{b}ARexx interface@{ub}

  The commands:

   @{" SHOW             " Link AX_Show}
   @{" HIDE             " Link AX_Hide}

   @{" REQUESTUSER      " Link AX_RequestUser}
   @{" REQUESTSTRING    " Link AX_RequestString}
   @{" REQUESTNUMBER    " Link AX_RequestNumber}

   @{" GETFILE          " Link AX_GetFile}
   @{" GETPATH          " Link AX_GetPath}

   @{" LOADFILE         " Link AX_LoadFile}
   @{" LOADNEW          " Link AX_LoadNew}
   @{" LOADANDSHOW      " Link AX_LoadAndShow}
   @{" LOADFROMFILEBASE " Link AX_LoadFromFileBase}
   @{" LOADFROMPATHBASE " Link AX_LoadFromPathBase}
   @{" LOADASAMIGAGUIDE " Link AX_LoadAsAmigaGuide}
   @{" LOADASTEXT       " Link AX_LoadAsText}
   @{" PRINT            " Link AX_Print}
   @{" SAVE             " Link AX_Save}

   @{" CLEAR            " Link AX_Clear}
   @{" CLEARALL         " Link AX_ClearAll}

   @{" SWITCHTEXTFONT   " Link AX_SwitchTextFont}

   @{" SEARCH           " Link AX_Search}
@ENDNODE

@NODE AX_Show "ARexx command: SHOW"

 @{b}SHOW@{ub}

  NAME
    SHOW - Show Vinci's screen.

  SYNOPSIS
    SHOW

  FUNCTION
    You should use this command just before the first time in the script
    Vinci might want to write something to the user in its window. E.g.
    if you would use Loadfile because Loadfile does not open the
    interface.

  INPUTS
    None

  RESULTS
    None
@ENDNODE

@NODE AX_Hide "ARexx command: HIDE"

 @{b}HIDE@{ub}

  NAME
    HIDE - Hide Vinci's screen.

  SYNOPSIS
    HIDE

  FUNCTION
    Hides Vinci's interface. 

  INPUTS
    None

  RESULTS
    None
@ENDNODE

@NODE AX_RequestUser "ARexx command: REQUESTUSER"

 @{b}REQUESTUSER@{ub}

  NAME
    REQUESTUSER - Request a response from the user

  SYNOPSIS
    REQUESTUSER T=TITLE/K,P=PROMPT/K/A,R=RESPONSE/K

  FUNCTION
    Request a response from the user.

  INPUTS
    Title    - The title of the requester. Default is 'Vinci Information'.
    Prompt   - The body text.
    Response - The gadgets. Default is 'Okay'. To have several responses
               separate the gadget texts with vertical bars. E.g.:
               'Okay|Maybe|Cancel'.

  RESULTS
    For @{b}RESPONSE@{ub} passed as @{b}Okay|Maybe|Cancel@{ub} it will return 1 for
    @{b}Okay@{ub}, 2 for @{b}Maybe@{ub} and 0 for @{b}Cancel@{ub}. The rightmost gadget will
    always return 0.
@ENDNODE

@NODE AX_RequestString "ARexx command: REQUESTSTRING"

 @{b}REQUESTSTRING@{ub}

  NAME
    REQUESTSTRING - Request a string from the user

  SYNOPSIS
    REQUESTSTRING T=TITLE/K,P=PROMPT/K,S=STRING/K,M=MAXBUFLEN/N,
                  A=ALLOWEMPTY/S,R=RESPONSE/K

  FUNCTION
    Get a string from the user.

  INPUTS
    Title      - Refer to @{"REQUESTUSER" Link AX_RequestUser}
    Prompt     - Refer to @{"REQUESTUSER" Link AX_RequestUser}
    String     - A default string to put in the string gadget.
    Maxbuflen  - Max number of characters allowed in string. May not be
                 more than 255. If not specified it defaults to 255.
                 May not be 0.
    Allowempty - Usually pressing return with an empty string gadget will
                 cancel the requester. Specify ALLOWEMPTY for allowing
                 empty strings.
    Response   - Refer to @{"REQUESTUSER" Link AX_RequestUser}


  RESULTS
     
@ENDNODE

@NODE AX_RequestNumber "ARexx command: REQUESTNUMBER"

 @{b}REQUESTNUMBER@{ub}

  NAME
    REQUESTNUMBER - Request a number from the user

  SYNOPSIS
    REQUESTNUMBER T=TITLE/K,P=PROMPT/K,M=MIN/N,X=MAX/N,N=NUMBER/N,
                  S=SHOWDEFAULT/S,R=RESPONSE/K

  FUNCTION
    Get an integer number from the user.

  INPUTS
    Title       - Refer to @{"REQUESTUSER" Link AX_RequestUser}
    Prompt      - Refer to @{"REQUESTUSER" Link AX_RequestUser}
    Min         - Minimum value allowed.
    Max         - Maximum value allowed.
    Number      - A default number to put in the integer gadget.
    Showdefault - If specified the value in NUMBER will be shown and
                  otherwise hidden.
    Response    - Refer to @{"REQUESTUSER" Link AX_RequestUser}

  RESULTS
    None
@ENDNODE

@NODE AX_GetFile "ARexx command: GETFILE"

 @{b}GETFILE@{ub}

  NAME
    GETFILE - Get a filename

  SYNOPSIS
    GETFILE T=TITLE/K,P=PATH/K,F=FILE/K

  FUNCTION
    Get a filename from the user.

  INPUTS
    Title - The title of the requester.
    Path  - The path which to position the requester in. If you know that
            a file always is in 'S:' you could pass 'S:' here to unburden
            the user.
    File  - A standard filename without leading path.

  RESULTS
    If the requester was canceled @{b}RC@{ub} will be 5. Otherwise 0 and @{b}RESULT@{ub}
    will then hold the selected filename including possible leading path.
@ENDNODE

@NODE AX_GetPath "ARexx command: GETPATH"

 @{b}GETPATH@{ub}

  NAME
    GETPATH - Get a path

  SYNOPSIS
    GETPATH T=TITLE/K,P=PATH/K

  FUNCTION
    Get a path from the user.

  INPUTS
    Title - The title of the requester.
    Path  - The path which to position the requester in.

  RESULTS
    If the requester was canceled @{b}RC@{ub} will be 5. Otherwise 0 and @{b}RESULT@{ub}
    will then hold the selected path.
@ENDNODE

@NODE AX_LoadFile "ARexx command: LOADFILE"

 @{b}LOADFILE@{ub}

  NAME
    LOADFILE - Load a file

  SYNOPSIS
    LOADFILE F=FILENAME/K/A,M=MODE/N/A

  FUNCTION
    Load a file into Vinci where it will be shown.

  INPUTS
    Filename - The name of the file to load.
    Mode     - A number. One of the following:

                1 - Load new
                2 - Load and show
                3 - Load as AmigaGuide
                4 - Load as text

  RESULTS
    None
@ENDNODE

@NODE AX_LoadNew "ARexx command: LOADNEW"

 @{b}LOADNEW@{ub}

  NAME
    LOADNEW - Load new file.

  SYNOPSIS
    LOADNEW

  FUNCTION
    Equivalent to selecting @{"Load new" LINK MI_LoadNew} in the menu.

  INPUTS
    None

  RESULTS
    None
@ENDNODE

@NODE AX_LoadAndShow "ARexx command: LOADANDSHOW"

 @{b}LOADANDSHOW@{ub}

  NAME
    LOADANDSHOW - Load and show a file

  SYNOPSIS
    LOADANDSHOW

  FUNCTION
    Equivalent to selecting @{"Load and show" LINK MI_LoadAndShow} in the menu.

  INPUTS
    None

  RESULTS
    None
@ENDNODE

@NODE AX_LoadFromFileBase "ARexx command: LOADFROMFILEBASE"

 @{b}LOADFROMFILEBASE@{ub}

  NAME
    LOADFROMFILEBASE - Load a file from the filebase list.

  SYNOPSIS
    LOADFROMFILEBASE

  FUNCTION
    Equivalent to selecting @{"Load from file base" LINK MI_LoadFromFileBase} in the menu.

  INPUTS
    None

  RESULTS
    None
@ENDNODE

@NODE AX_LoadFromPathBase "ARexx command: LOADFROMPATHBASE"

 @{b}LOADFROMPATHBASE@{ub}

  NAME
    LOADFROMPATHBASE - Load a file via the path base.

  SYNOPSIS
    LOADFROMPATHBASE

  FUNCTION
