@NODE ReFormatUsage "How to use ReFormat"

 @{b}Usage@{ub}

  ReFormat is simply a little tool that reformats a PC text. It replaces
  the PC's carriage return & line feed that represents a new line to a
  line feed.

  Type 'ReFormat ?' to see the command line interface of ReFormat.

  It looks like this:

   S=SOURCEFILE/K/A,D=DESTINATIONFILE/K/A,AO=AUTOOVERWRITE/S,R=REMOVECRLF/S


   @{b}SOURCEFILE@{ub} abbreviation S  (required argument)
   
    The name of the file you want to reformat.

   @{b}DESTINATIONFILE@{ub} abbreviation D  (required argument)
   
    The name of the reformatted file. May be the same name as given in
    @{b}SOURCEFILE@{ub}. If so ReFormat asks if it should overwrite the file.
    This request can be surpressed using the @{b}AUTOOVERWRITE@{ub} argument
    described below.

   @{b}AUTOOVERWRITE@{ub} abbreviation AO
   
    If this argument is specified ReFormat will not ask if it should
    overwrite a file.

   @{b}REMOVECRLF@{ub} abbreviation R
   
    To actually reformat a PC text you have to specify this argument. A
    bit silly to specify since this is the only function ReFormat has
    right now. I made it because I intend to add more reformat functions
    to ReFormat at a later point.
@ENDNODE

@NODE ReFormatHistory "History of ReFormat"

 @{b}History@{ub}

  Version:

   @{" 1.0 " LINK REFORMATVERS_10}
@ENDNODE

